Prostomium triangular, short, with a palpode (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
); nuchal organs not everted; eyespots as small black dots (more than 15 each side), distributed obliquely on each side of prostomium. Proboscis globular-shaped, weakly papillated with short papillae (
Fig. 4D
); papillae with filamentous sensory cilia (
Fig. 5C
). Peristomium half-length of thoracic chaetigers (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
).

Thorax with 13 chaetigers. First chaetiger uniramous. Unilimbate capillaries in notopodia of chaetigers 1–13 and in neuropodia of chaetigers 2–12; neuropodium of chaetiger 13 with hooded hooks. Peristomium and first five chaetigers with strongly tessellated epithelium, subsequent chaetigers smooth (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
). Chaetigers 6–13 biannulate, divided in anterior and posterior portions to chaetal bundle, and with extremities strongly angled (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
); chaetae emerging from middle of segment; and with a mid-lateral lobe (MLL) between noto- and neuropodial chaetae and below lateral organ (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
). Notochaetae inserted dorso- laterally, bundles becoming closer and completely inserted dorsally on last 2–3 thoracic chaetigers; neurochaetae inserted ventro-laterally in the middle of the segment throughout. Chaetigers 1–5 with thick, white line ventrally (WVL) in the middle of segment, forming a continuous line (
Fig. 4D
). Lateral organs (LO) present from chaetiger 1 bearing short sensory cilia (
Fig. 5A; D
). Epithelia around lateral organ with small, rounded sensory furrows (SF) (
Fig. 5D
). Transition between thorax and abdomen evident, distinguished by the appearance of parapodial lobes and hooks, and by increasing width (
Figs 3A
; 
5A
).

Abdominal chaetigers with hooded hooks throughout. Large and globulous lateral organs throughout abdomen (
Fig. 3B
); lateral organ with long and numerous sensory cilia (C) (
Fig. 5E
). Notopodia with a unique globulous lobe; hooded hooks inserted dorsally, both bundles almost together, separated by a rounded part of the lobe (
Figs 3B
; 
4A
). Neuropodia with thin and poorly developed lobes, with an expansion projecting dorsally as a tip (
Figs 3A
; 
4A
; 
5B
); hooded hooks inserted ventral and laterally, in a long line. Abdominal chaetigers larger ventrally and narrower dorsally, chaetae emerging from last third of segment. First abdominal notopodia with 17 hooks per fascicle, decreasing on last chaetigers of abdomen; first abdominal neuropodia with 36 hooks per fascicle, decreasing on last chaetigers of abdomen. Notopodial hooks with long and large main fang, surmounted by approximately 12 teeth arranged in three rows (3–2–7) (
Fig. 5F
). Neuropodial hooks with long, thin and pointed main fang, surmounted by approximately 10 teeth arranged in three rows (2–1–7) (
Fig. 5G
). Small notopodial expansions (“branchiae”) inserted dorsally, but laterally on the notopodial lobe, beginning after segment 47; first expansions small and triangular (
Fig. 4B
), becoming more filamentous (branched) toward posterior end (up to seven filaments) (
Fig. 4C, F
). Pygidium unknown.

Methyl green staining pattern (MGSP).
Thorax staining darker than abdomen; chaetigers 1–4 staining lighter than remaining thoracic chaetigers (
Fig. 4E
). Dorsal region of abdomen with a large continuous dark band throughout (
Fig. 4E
). Posteriormost segments with a dorsal dark band near the division between each segment (
Fig. 4F
).
